<h1>Introduction to Python</h1>
<p>Welcome to the first lesson of our Python course! In this lesson, we will cover the
     basics of Python programming, including syntax, variables, and data types. By the end of this lesson, 
     you will have a solid foundation to start writing your own Python code.</p>
<h2>Python Syntax</h2>
<p>Python uses indentation to define blocks of code. This means that instead of using 
    curly braces or keywords to indicate the start and end of a block, Python 
    relies on the level of indentation. For example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">if x &gt; 0:
    print("x is positive")
else:
    print("x is not positive")
</code></pre>
<p>In this example, the code inside the if and else blocks is indented, indicating
     that it belongs to those blocks.</p>
<h2>Variables</h2>
<p>In Python, you can create variables to store data. A variable is created by 
    assigning a value to it using the equals sign (=). For example:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">name = "Alice"
age = 30
is_student = True
</code></pre>
<p>In this example, we have created three variables: name, age, and is_student. 
    The name variable stores a string, the age variable stores an integer, and 
    the is_student variable stores a boolean value.</p>
<h2>Data Types</h2>
<p>Python has several built-in data types, including:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>String:</strong> A sequence of characters, enclosed in quotes.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">name = "Alice"</code></pre>
    <li><strong>Integer:</strong> A whole number.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">number = 42</code></pre>
    <li><strong>Float:</strong> A decimal number.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">pi = 3.14</code></pre>
    <li><strong>Boolean:</strong> A value that can be either True or False.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">is_student = True</code></pre>
    <li><strong>List:</strong> An ordered collection of items, enclosed in square brackets.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]</code></pre>
    <li><strong>Dictionary:</strong> A collection of key-value pairs, enclosed in curly braces.</li>
    <pre><code class="language-python">person = {"name": "Alice", "age": 30}</code></pre>
</ul>

<p>Understanding these basic data types is essential for writing effective Python code. 
    In the next lesson, we will explore control structures, which allow you to control
     the flow of your program based on certain conditions.</p>
    
